    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-10-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-10-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="306"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d306">
                <head>306. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_BWH2" type="from">William H.
                        Brubeck</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF2" type="to">Kennedy</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d306fn0">Source: <persName corresp="#p_KJF2"
                            >Kennedy</persName> Library, National Security Files, Countries, Somali
                        Republic. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-10-25">October 25, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>This is the first time you have seen <persName corresp="#p_THGJ1">Horace
                        Torbert</persName>, our Ambassador to Somalia. He has been in Mogadiscio,
                    his first Ambassadorial post, since December 1962, is career Foreign Service
                    Officer whose background is mostly Western and Central Europe.</p>
                <p>You remember that <persName corresp="#p_HSI1">Haile Selassie</persName>
                    complained about our military aid to the Somalis and you promised to reexamine
                    it after we found out what deal the Somalis were making in Moscow.</p>
                <p>The Somalis are about to accept a $30 million Soviet military aid package knowing
                    that they will thus lose an $18 million five-year US-German-Italian
                        program.<note n="1" xml:id="d306fn1">At a tripartite meeting in Bonn October
                        17-18, U.S., German, and Italian representatives reached agreement on a
                        joint military aid package for Somalia. (Telegram 1413 from Bonn, October
                        18; Department of State, Central Files, DEF 19 SOMALI)</note> Although they
                    are Western oriented their primary drive is a military strength (which they
                    can’t afford) to back up their quarrel with the Ethiopians and Kenya over
                    borders.</p>
                <p>In addition to our small economic aid program the Somalis have received large aid
                    grants from the Chicoms and Russians.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWH2">
                            <hi rend="strong">William H. Brubeck</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d306fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
